        "label": "Feedback Network",
        "color": "blue",
        "variant": "filled"
      },
      "style": {
        "width": 310,
        "height": 710
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "sc-note-1",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 920,
        "y": 160
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "What does this do?",
        "text": "Soft clipping gradually rounds off the signal peaks, adding warm, smooth overdrive. The op-amp's feedback loop compresses the signal instead of chopping it flat.",
        "color": "yellow",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "sc-note-compare",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 920,
        "y": 260
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Same diodes, different result",
        "text": "Compare this to the Hard Clipping example — both use 1N914 silicon diodes! But here they're in the feedback loop (soft), not shunting to ground (hard). Topology matters more than the diode type.",
        "color": "yellow",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "sc-note-gain",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 860,
        "y": 500
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Gain control (R2)",
        "text": "R2 sets the gain: R2/R1 = 100k/10k = 10×. As gain increases, the signal hits the diode threshold sooner, creating more overdrive. In the Tube Screamer, this is the Drive knob.",
        "color": "blue",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "sc-note-diodes",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 860,
        "y": 600
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Feedback diodes (D1 + D2)",
        "text": "D1 and D2 sit in parallel with R2. At low levels, R2 sets the gain normally. As output grows past ~0.7V, the diodes conduct and effectively reduce R2's resistance — compressing the peaks smoothly.",
        "color": "purple",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "sc-note-bias",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 660,
        "y": 110
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Bias divider (R4 + R5)",
        "text": "Equal resistors split VCC in half (4.5V), centering the signal in the op-amp's linear range. Unequal values would shift the bias point — clipping one half of the waveform harder than the other.",
        "color": "blue",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "sc-note-bypass",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 340,
        "y": 230
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Bypass cap (C3)",
        "text": "Holds the bias voltage steady at audio frequencies. Without it, signal leaks into the bias node and causes oscillation. Larger values keep the bias stable at lower frequencies.",
        "color": "blue",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
